TradingSystem — A C++ Forex Order Matching Engine with Live React UI
====================================================================


Introduction
------------

TradingSystem is a fully functional, in-memory foreign exchange order matching
engine written in modern C++17. It accepts buy and sell orders for currency
pairs, maintains a live order book with strict price-time priority, executes
SPOT trades automatically when bid and ask prices cross, and delivers real-time
notifications to connected web clients via Server-Sent Events (SSE).

The system exposes a REST API over HTTP so that orders can be submitted and
cancelled programmatically or through its companion React UI. When a trade
executes, both counterparties are notified immediately, the fill is recorded in
a recent-trade ring buffer, and every connected browser receives a live update
within milliseconds — all without polling.

The project was built with no external C++ dependencies beyond a single-header
HTTP library. The matching engine, order book, event bus, and HTTP server are
all hand-coded in standard C++. The React front-end uses Vite, Zustand for
state management, and plain CSS — no UI framework.


Structure
---------

The project is split into three layers: a C++ backend, a React frontend, and a
set of shell scripts and data files for running and testing the system.

C++ Backend

The backend is organised around ten classes, each with a focused
responsibility:

  Order           Represents a single resting or incoming order. Holds the
                  trading symbol, price, quantity, order type, and a non-owning
                  pointer to the counterparty that submitted it. A static
                  std::atomic<long> counter provides thread-safe, auto-
                  incrementing order IDs.

  OrderType       An enum whose even values are buy-side types and odd values
                  are sell-side types. isBuyOrder() and isSellOrder() exploit
                  this arithmetic convention with a single bitwise test, making
                  side classification branch-free.

  Counterparty    Represents a trading firm. Tracks its open order IDs and
                  receives TradeNotification structs when its orders fill.
                  Counterparty objects are owned by the caller; Order holds
                  only a raw, non-owning pointer.

  SubBook         The per-symbol order container. Holds two sorted maps: a
                  BidMap (std::map with std::greater comparator, so begin()
                  is the highest bid) and an AskMap (std::map with default
                  ascending order, so begin() is the lowest ask). Each price
                  level in both maps stores a std::list<Order> in strict FIFO
                  arrival order.

  OrderBook       The top-level registry. Maps trading symbols to SubBooks via
                  std::unordered_map for O(1) symbol lookup, and maintains a
                  second unordered_map from order ID to OrderLocation for O(1)
                  cancellation without scanning the book.

  TradeManager    Contains all matching logic. matchSpotOrders walks the
                  opposite side of the book from the best price inward,
                  executing fills for as long as prices cross and quantity
                  remains. logAndNotify records each fill, publishes an SSE
                  trade event, and calls onTrade() on both counterparties.

  OrderManager    Orchestrates the order lifecycle. For SPOT orders it calls
                  the matching engine first, then queues any unfilled remainder.
                  For all other order types it queues immediately. After every
                  state change it publishes a book_update SSE event.

  EventBus        A thread-safe publish/subscribe bus. Each SSE connection
                  receives a shared_ptr<Connection> that owns a message queue,
                  a mutex, and a condition variable. publish() pushes a message
                  to every live connection and wakes their waiting threads.

  HTTPServer      Wraps cpp-httplib to expose the REST API and the SSE
                  /events endpoint. All OrderManager access is serialised
                  through a single mutex. The SSE handler blocks on its
                  connection's condition variable without holding that mutex,
                  so live streams never stall incoming REST requests.

  MarketManager   A stub placeholder for a future live market data feed.

React Frontend (ui/)

The UI is a single-page React application built with Vite:

  App.jsx              Top-level component. Fetches initial state on mount,
                       opens the SSE EventSource, and distributes live data
                       as props to child components.

  tradingStore.js      Zustand store holding books, trades, symbols, and
                       connection state. Components receive data as props from
                       App rather than subscribing independently, ensuring
                       all children update in the same render cycle.

  MarketSummary.jsx    Horizontal summary grid above the main panels. Shows
                       best bid, best ask, quantity, last trade price with
                       direction arrow, and time of last trade per symbol.
                       Cells flash gold for two seconds on any change.

  OrderBook.jsx        Price ladder showing all bid and ask levels for the
                       selected symbol.

  TradeFeed.jsx        Scrolling log of recent fills.

  OrderForm.jsx        Form for submitting new orders and cancelling by ID.

Shell Scripts and Data

  run_server.sh        Compiles the C++ binary and starts the HTTP server.
  run_ui.sh            Installs npm dependencies and starts the Vite dev server.
  run_orders_loop.sh   Submits all 100 CSV orders via REST in a loop,
                       cancelling all open orders between iterations.
  demo_trade.sh        Submits a single bid/offer pair that results in a trade.
  demo_rising_price.sh Submits two consecutive trades at increasing prices,
                       demonstrating the direction arrow in the UI.
  forex_orders.csv     100 sample forex orders across 25 currency pairs.


Architecture
------------

The central design decision is the separation of the order book data structure
from the matching logic. The book exists purely to store and retrieve orders
efficiently; the matching engine operates on it from the outside.

Order Book Data Structures

Each symbol has its own SubBook containing two sorted maps:

  BidMap — std::map<double, std::list<Order>, std::greater<double>>
  AskMap — std::map<double, std::list<Order>>

Using std::greater for bids means the map's begin() iterator always points to
the highest bid. The AskMap's begin() always points to the lowest ask. In both
cases the best price is available in O(1) without any search or reverse
iteration.

Within each price level, orders are stored in a std::list<Order>. std::list
provides O(1) insertion at the back (preserving arrival order) and, critically,
O(1) erasure of any node given its iterator — without invalidating any other
iterator in the list. This property is essential for cancellation.

O(1) Cancellation via OrderLocation

When an order is queued, an OrderLocation struct is created and stored in a
second unordered_map<long, OrderLocation> keyed by order ID:

  struct OrderLocation {
      std::list<Order>*           priceList;   // pointer to the level's list
      double                      price;       // key in the parent map
      std::list<Order>::iterator  it;          // direct iterator to the order
      std::function<void(double)> eraseLevel;  // type-erased map erase call
  };

Cancelling an order is then four steps, each O(1):
  1. Hash-map lookup of the OrderLocation by order ID.
  2. list::erase(it) to remove the order node.
  3. If the list is now empty, call eraseLevel(price) to remove the price-level
     entry from the map.
  4. Erase the OrderLocation from the index.

The eraseLevel field is a lambda captured at insert time. Because BidMap and
AskMap are different C++ types, a single raw pointer cannot erase from both.
The lambda closes over the map by reference and hides the type difference
behind a std::function<void(double)>. This is a deliberate use of type erasure
to keep OrderLocation generic.

Event Flow

State changes flow outward via the EventBus. After every order queue or cancel,
OrderManager serialises the current SubBook to JSON and calls
EventBus::publish("event: book_update\ndata: {...}\n\n"). After every fill,
TradeManager calls EventBus::publish("event: trade\ndata: {...}\n\n"). Each
publish call iterates every live SSE connection, pushes the message to its
queue, and calls notify_one() on its condition variable, waking the SSE handler
thread to flush the chunk to the browser.

Thread Safety

The HTTP server uses a single coarse-grained mutex around all OrderManager
calls. The SSE handler acquires only the per-connection mutex while draining
its queue, not the global mutex, so it never blocks order processing.


Order Entry
-----------

The journey of an order from submission to the book passes through four layers.

1. HTTP Receipt

   The React UI posts JSON to POST /orders. HTTPServer parses the body with
   simple string-search extractors (no JSON library dependency), resolves the
   named counterparty from an internal map, constructs an Order object, and
   calls OrderManager::processNewOrder() under the global mutex.

2. Matching Attempt

   For SPOT_BUY and SPOT_SELL orders, processNewOrder immediately calls
   TradeManager::matchSpotOrders() with a mutable copy of the order. The
   matching engine walks the opposite side of the book from the best price
   inward, executing fills for as long as prices cross and quantity remains.
   If the order is fully filled, matchSpotOrders returns true and the order
   is not queued.

3. Queuing

   If any quantity remains after matching (or if the order type is not SPOT),
   queueOrder inserts it into the appropriate price-level list:

     (*BidMap or AskMap)[price].push_back(order)   — O(log n) map insert
                                                      or O(1) if level exists

   It then registers the order in the cancellation index:

     orderIndex[id] = OrderLocation{&list, price, iter, eraseLevel}

   And notifies the counterparty:

     counterparty->addOrderId(id)

4. Book Update Event

   After queuing (or after a full fill), publishBookUpdate serialises the
   entire SubBook for the affected symbol to JSON and calls
   EventBus::publish(). Every connected browser receives the update within
   the SSE flush latency.

Order Entry Sequence (no matching trade)

  Client           HTTPServer        OrderBook         TradeManager       EventBus
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |  POST /orders     |                |                   |                |
    |------------------>|                |                   |                |
    |                   |  addOrder()    |                   |                |
    |                   |--------------->|                   |                |
    |                   |                |  matchSpotOrders()|                |
    |                   |                |------------------>|                |
    |                   |                |                   | (no match)     |
    |                   |                |<------------------|                |
    |                   |                |  queue in SubBook |                |
    |                   |                |  update index     |                |
    |                   |                |  publishBookUpdate|                |
    |                   |                |---------------------------------->|
    |                   |                |                   |  SSE: book_update
    |                   |                |                   |                |---> browsers
    |  201 Created      |                |                   |                |
    |<------------------|                |                   |                |

Cancellation follows a simpler path: getOrderSymbol and getOrderCounterparty
read from the existing index entry before erasure, OrderBook::cancel removes
the order in O(1), removeOrderId cleans up the counterparty, and another
book_update event is published.

Order Cancellation Sequence

  Client           HTTPServer        OrderBook         Counterparty       EventBus
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    | DELETE /orders/id |                |                   |                |
    |------------------>|                |                   |                |
    |                   |  cancel(id)    |                   |                |
    |                   |--------------->|                   |                |
    |                   |                | look up index     |                |
    |                   |                | erase from list   |                |
    |                   |                | removeFromIndex() |                |
    |                   |                | removeOrderId()   |                |
    |                   |                |------------------>|                |
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |                   |                | publishBookUpdate |                |
    |                   |                |---------------------------------->|
    |                   |                |                   |  SSE: book_update
    |                   |                |                   |                |---> browsers
    |  200 OK           |                |                   |                |
    |<------------------|                |                   |                |


Trading Engine
--------------

The matching algorithm in TradeManager::matchSpotOrders implements continuous,
price-time priority matching — the same fundamental model used in real foreign
exchange markets.

Price Crossing

A trade occurs when a buyer's limit price is at or above a seller's limit
price: pricesMatch(bid, ask) returns bid >= ask. This inclusive condition means
orders at exactly equal prices always execute.

Walk from Best Price Inward

For an incoming SPOT_BUY:
  - The engine iterates AskMap from begin() (lowest ask) forward.
  - At each price level it checks pricesMatch. If the best ask already exceeds
    the bid's limit, the loop exits immediately — no fill is possible.
  - Within a price level, orders fill in strict FIFO order (the oldest resting
    ask fills first).

For an incoming SPOT_SELL the logic is symmetric: BidMap is iterated from
begin() (highest bid) forward.

Execution Price

Every trade executes at the standing (resting) order's price, not the
incoming order's price. This is the maker/taker model: the order already in
the book set the price; the incoming order accepts it.

Partial Fills

When a fill only partially consumes the standing order, the engine calls
standing.setQuantity(remaining) to update its quantity in-place. The order's
position in the list does not change and its OrderLocation remains valid.

When a fill fully consumes the standing order:
  - level.erase(orderIt) removes the node in O(1) and returns the next
    iterator, keeping the inner loop correct without a manual advance.
  - book.removeFromIndex(standingId) strips the now-stale index entry.
  - counterparty->removeOrderId(standingId) updates tracking.
  - If the price level is now empty, asks.erase(mapIt) removes it from the map.

Cascade Fills

Because the outer loop continues across price levels, a single large incoming
order can sweep through multiple price levels in one call, executing fills at
each. The incoming order's quantity is decremented after each fill; the loop
exits only when it reaches zero or when no more crossing prices exist.

The return value of matchSpotOrders is simply incoming.getQuantity() == 0.
If true, the caller does not queue the order. If false, the reduced-quantity
remainder is queued at its original limit price.

Trade Execution Sequence (incoming buy matches resting sell)

  Client           HTTPServer        OrderBook         TradeManager       EventBus
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |  POST /orders     |                |                   |                |
    |  (SPOT_BUY)       |                |                   |                |
    |------------------>|                |                   |                |
    |                   |  addOrder()    |                   |                |
    |                   |--------------->|                   |                |
    |                   |                | matchSpotOrders() |                |
    |                   |                |------------------>|                |
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |                   |                |                   | walk AskMap    |
    |                   |                |                   | pricesMatch()  |
    |                   |                |                   | fillQty = min  |
    |                   |                |                   |   (bid,ask qty)|
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |                   |                |     [repeat for each fill]         |
    |                   |                |                   | logAndNotify() |
    |                   |                |                   |--------------->|
    |                   |                |                   |  SSE: trade    |
    |                   |                |                   |                |---> browsers
    |                   |                |                   | buyer.onTrade()|
    |                   |                |                   | seller.onTrade()|
    |                   |                |                   |                |
    |                   |                |<------------------|                |
    |                   |                | (fully filled: do not queue)       |
    |                   |                | publishBookUpdate |                |
    |                   |                |---------------------------------->|
    |                   |                |                   |  SSE: book_update
    |                   |                |                   |                |---> browsers
    |  201 Created      |                |                   |                |
    |<------------------|                |                   |                |


User Interface
--------------

The React UI is a single-page application served by Vite in development mode
(or from a static build). It connects to the C++ server over REST and SSE.

Layout

The page is a CSS grid with four rows: a fixed header bar, a scrollable market
summary panel that spans full width, a two-column main area (order book on the
left, trade feed on the right), and a fixed order-entry footer.

Real-Time Updates

App.jsx opens a single EventSource to GET /events on mount. Incoming SSE
events are routed to the Zustand store:

  book_update → updateBook(parsed)  — updates books[symbol] and bookTimes[symbol]
  trade       → addTrade(parsed)    — prepends to trades[], capped at 100

All child components receive data as props from App rather than subscribing to
the store independently. This ensures every component re-renders in the same
React cycle when an event arrives, preventing visual inconsistency.

Market Summary

The MarketSummary component tracks per-symbol best bid, best ask, quantity,
last trade price, and time of last trade. It uses two useRef objects to avoid
stale-closure issues:

  prevRef    Stores the previous values of all tracked fields for each symbol.
             Updated inside a useEffect after renders, not during them.

  timersRef  Stores setTimeout handles for gold-flash expiry, one per cell key.

When a value changes, the component calls triggerFlash(key), which sets a
boolean in the flashing state map and schedules its removal after two seconds.
CSS handles the visual: .ms-cell.flash sets color to gold with transition: none
(instant appearance), and removing the class restores the default grey with a
0.4s ease transition (smooth fade).

The direction arrow next to the last trade price is computed by comparing the
current last trade price against prevLastTrade (the price from the render
before the current one). This value is stored separately from lastTrade in
prevRef so that the render always has access to the prior price even after the
useEffect has updated lastTrade to the new value.

The API base URL is derived from window.location.hostname so the UI works both
locally (localhost:9090) and from other machines on the network without any
configuration change.

Clear Button

The Clear button in the header cancels all open orders by fetching GET /books,
collecting every order ID across all symbols and price levels, then issuing
DELETE /orders/:id for each sequentially. Sequential (rather than parallel)
cancellation avoids overwhelming the server's thread pool. Up to three passes
are made to catch any orders added during a prior pass. After cancellation it
clears the trade history from the Zustand store and increments a clearKey prop
passed to MarketSummary, which resets its internal trade-time and previous-
price tracking state.


Core Lessons
------------

Several areas of the implementation showcase specific C++ features and idioms
worth highlighting.

Type Erasure with std::function

BidMap and AskMap are distinct C++ types (both are std::map but with different
comparators). A single generic OrderLocation struct must be able to erase a
price level from either without knowing which one it belongs to. The solution
is to capture the map erase operation at insert time as a
std::function<void(double)> lambda:

  std::function<void(double)> eraseLevel = [&bids](double p) {
      bids.erase(p);
  };

The lambda closes over the concrete map, hiding its type behind the uniform
function signature. cancel() calls eraseLevel(price) without any branching
or dynamic_cast.

Iterator Stability of std::list

std::list guarantees that inserting or erasing any node does not invalidate
iterators to other nodes. The matching engine exploits this heavily: it stores
a std::list<Order>::iterator in OrderLocation and calls list::erase(it)
directly during cancellation in O(1). Inside the matching loop it advances the
iterator before erasing (orderIt = level.erase(orderIt)), ensuring the loop
variable is always valid regardless of how many nodes are consumed.

Atomic ID Generation

Order and Counterparty each use a static std::atomic<long> counter incremented
with fetch_add(1, std::memory_order_relaxed). This gives unique, monotonically
increasing IDs across all instances with no locking.

Condition Variables for SSE Back-Pressure

Each SSE connection is a shared_ptr<Connection> that owns a
std::condition_variable. The SSE handler thread blocks on cv.wait_for(20s)
rather than busy-waiting. EventBus::publish() wakes exactly the threads that
have work by calling cv.notify_one() per connection under that connection's
mutex. The 20-second wait_for doubles as a keepalive heartbeat: if no event
arrives, the handler sends an SSE comment line (": keepalive\n\n") to keep the
connection alive through proxies.

Move Semantics in Order Queuing

Orders are pushed into the price-level lists by value. The compiler uses move
semantics where possible, avoiding unnecessary copies of the Order struct when
it is constructed in-place from the HTTP handler and forwarded into the list.

Non-Owning Pointers as Observer Pattern

Order holds a raw Counterparty* with no ownership semantics. This deliberately
signals that Order does not manage the counterparty's lifetime — Counterparty
objects are owned by the application shell (TradingSystem.cpp or HTTPServer)
and outlive any individual order. The pattern avoids reference-counting overhead
while making ownership relationships explicit in the type system.

Lazy Initialisation via operator[]

OrderBook::get(symbol) is a one-liner:

  SubBook& OrderBook::get(const std::string& symbol) {
      return books[symbol];
  }

std::unordered_map::operator[] default-constructs the value if the key is
absent. A SubBook default-constructs to empty BidMap and AskMap. No explicit
"create if absent" logic is needed anywhere.


Conclusion
----------

TradingSystem demonstrates that a correct, low-latency order matching engine
with real-time UI streaming can be built in a few thousand lines of standard
C++ and React, without any external C++ library beyond a single-header HTTP
server.

The most natural next steps fall into several areas:

Matching Engine Completeness
  The current engine only matches SPOT orders. LIMIT orders (fill or rest at a
  specific price), STOP orders (trigger on price breach), and SWAP orders each
  require their own matching rules and book representations. Adding them would
  turn the system into a full multi-instrument matching engine.

Persistence
  All state is in-memory. Adding a write-ahead log or a database backend would
  allow the book to survive process restarts and enable replay of historical
  order flow for back-testing.

Market Data Integration
  MarketManager is currently a stub. Connecting it to a live WebSocket or FIX
  feed would let the engine price non-SPOT orders against a reference rate and
  detect stop triggers automatically.

Order Amendment
  Orders can currently only be submitted or cancelled. Modifying the price or
  quantity of a resting order (with appropriate queue-position rules) would
  bring the system closer to exchange-grade functionality.

Fine-Grained Concurrency
  The current design serialises all order processing behind a single mutex in
  HTTPServer. A production system would use per-symbol locks or a lock-free
  structure so that activity in EUR/USD does not block USD/JPY processing.

Position and Risk Management
  Tracking the net position per counterparty, enforcing position limits, and
  computing mark-to-market P&L would be the foundation of a proper risk layer.

Unified Counterparty Registry
  CSV-sourced counterparties and HTTP-submitted counterparties are currently
  separate objects. A shared registry would unify them and allow position
  tracking across both order sources.

The codebase is intentionally structured to make each of these extensions
straightforward: the matching engine is isolated in TradeManager, the book
storage is isolated in OrderBook and SubBook, and the HTTP interface is
isolated in HTTPServer. New features can be added to any layer without
touching the others.
